{{Infobox organization | name = American Society for Legal History | native_name = <!-- Organization's name in its local language --> | native_name_lang = <!-- ISO code of the above language --> | named_after = | image = | image_size = | alt = <!-- see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = | map = <!-- map image --> | map_size = <!-- defaults to 250px --> | map_alt = | map_caption = | map2 = <!-- second map image, if required --> | map2_size = | map2_alt = | map2_caption = | abbreviation = ASLH | motto = | predecessor = | merged = <!-- Any other organizations with which the organization was merged --> | successor = | formation = 1956 | founder = <!-- or: | founders = --> | founding_location = | extinction = <!-- or: | dissolved = --> <!--e.g. use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}--> | merger = <!-- Other organizations (if any) merged to constitute the organization --> | type = Nonprofit organization | status = Learned society | purpose = | professional_title = <!-- for professional associations --> | headquarters = | location = | coords = <!-- location's {{coord}}s --> | region = <!-- or: | region_served = --> <!--Any particular region or regions associated with or served by the organization--> | services = | membership = 1,100<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6GvdlpRu9-kC |title=United States History: A Multicultural, Interdisciplinary Guide to Information Sources |last=Perrault |first=Anna H. |last2=Blazek |first2=Ron |date=2003 |publisher=Libraries Unlimited |isbn=9781563088742 |pages=490 |language=en}}</ref> | membership_year = 2003 | language = <!-- or: | languages = --> <!--Any official language or languages used by the organization--> | sec_gen = <!-- Name of the organization's Secretary General (if post exists) --> | leader_title = President | leader_name = [[Sarah Barringer Gordon]] | leader_title2 = President-elect | leader_name2 = [[Lauren Benton (historian)|Lauren Benton]] | leader_title3 = Secretary | leader_name3 = Sally Hadden | leader_title4 = | leader_name4 = | board_of_directors = | key_people = | main_organ = <!-- or: | publication = --> <!--Organization's principal body (assembly, committee, board, etc) or publication--> | parent_organization = <!-- or: | parent_organisation = --> | subsidiaries = | secessions = | affiliations = | budget = | budget_year = | staff = <!-- Numbers and/or types of staff --> | staff_year = <!-- Year to which staff numbers/data apply --> | volunteers = <!-- Numbers and/or types of volunteers --> | volunteers_year = <!-- Year to which volunteer numbers/data apply --> | slogan = <!-- in quotemarks / inverted commas --> | website = <!-- e.g. {{url|example.com}} --> | remarks = | formerly = <!-- Any former names by which the organization known --> | footnotes = }} The '''American Society for Legal History''' is a learned society dedicated to promoting scholarship and teaching in the field of [[legal history]]. It was founded in 1956 and has an international scope, despite being based in [[the United States]]. It sponsors the [[peer-review]]ed journal ''[[Law and History Review]]'' and the book series ''Studies in Legal History'', both of which are published by [[Cambridge University Press]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/membership/aslh |title=American Society for Legal History |website=Cambridge Core |language=en |access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref> In 1957, the Society established the ''[[American Journal of Legal History]]'', which the Society originally published as its official journal. The journal was later acquired by the [[Temple University Beasley School of Law]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pv7sAgAAQBAJ |title=Journals of the Century |last=Cole |first=Jim |last2=Stankus |first2=Tony |date=2014-02-25 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781317720140|page=236 |language=en}}</ref> It has been a member of the [[American Council of Learned Societies]] since 1973.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.acls.org/ |title=American Society for Legal History |website=American Council of Learned Societies |access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref>
