{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Kim Sloan | honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|PhD|FSA|size=100%}} | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | awards = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Toronto]], [[University College London]] | thesis_title = | doctoral_advisor = | discipline = [[Art History]] | workplaces = [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], [[British Museum]] | notable_works = ''Enlightenment: Discovering the World in the Eighteenth Century'' }}
'''Dr Kim Sloan''' is a Canadian [[art historian]].
==Career== Sloan worked for the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in 1986 where she curated an exhibition on [[Alexander Cozens]] from November 1986-January 1987. The exhibition then traveled to the [[Art Gallery of Ontario]] with additional works by his son [[John Robert Cozens]] and was on display January–March 1987.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/alexanderjohnrob00sloa|title=Alexander and John Robert Cozens : the poetry of landscape|last=Sloan|first=Kim|last2=Art Gallery of Ontario|last3=Victoria and Albert Museum|date=1986|publisher=New Haven : Published in association with the Art Gallery of Ontario by Yale University Press|others=Internet Archive}}</ref>
In 1992, Sloan became the curator of British Drawings and Watercolours before 1880 at the [[British Museum]]. While at the [[British Museum]], Sloan has worked primarily on [[William Hamilton (diplomat)|Sir William Hamilton]] and his collections at the [[British Museum]], the watercolours of [[J. M. W. Turner]], and the [[Hans Sloane]] collections. From 2000, Sloan was the lead curator creating the new Enlightenment Gallery at the [[British Museum]], which presents the history of the collection in the [[King's Library]] after the library collection moved to the [[British Library]]. The new gallery opened in 2003 and Sloan maintains curatorial responsibility for the Enlightenment Gallery.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=COOTE|first=JEREMY|date=2007|title=Review of Enlightenment: Discovering the World in the Eighteenth Century|jstor=40793847|journal=Journal of Museum Ethnography|issue=19|pages=135–141}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wissenschaftliche-sammlungen.de/de/termine/kim-sloan-turning-kings-library-enlightenment-gallery-thirteen-years|title=Kim Sloan: "Turning the King's Library into the Enlightenment Gallery - thirteen years on" · Koordinierungsstelle wissenschaftliche Sammlungen|website=wissenschaftliche-sammlungen.de|language=en|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref>
From September 2007 - January 2008, Sloan was the Leverhulme Fellow at the [[National Portrait Gallery, London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/research/programmes/learn-more-research|title=Research programmes at the Gallery - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref>
==Bibliography== *''A Noble Art: Amateur Artists and Drawing Masters, C.1600-1800''. British Museum Press, 2000, 256 pages.
